Given the antagonistic nature of the defining U.S.-Soviet relationship during the Cold War, it makes sense that realism would be the prevailing theory.

Post-Cold War, realist theories have tended to focus on the potential for conflict posed by ethnic divisions, in which neighboring states seek power over each other by eliminating minority groups — as in the former Yugoslavia and the Balkans in the 90s.
